"Odd and curious" has two specific meanings:
1) on the Isle of Man, it is usual to name the common/general man: "the odd and curious". For example: 

"For the odd and curious of us, to fly like a bird a not an easy thing".

"The odd and curious is born good and pure. The society corrupts <i>it</i>.
(note: the personal pronoun for "the odd and curious" is always neutral)

2) In the United States, "odd and curious" is used to designate some special sort of coins, namely odd <i>and</i> curious coins, i.e. coins that are imperfect or seriously damaged, in opposition to normal coins.